body:
Hey @lucasfcosta. Thanks for the work on this. I think the implementation looks good overall, but I have a somewhat more philosophical question for this. How does this interact with the resource sanitizer?

An example to illustrate the issue:

```js
Deno.test("hello", { timeout: 5000 }, async () => {
  await new Promise(res => setTimeout(res, 10000));
});
```

The above test will time out after 5 seconds, but it will then subsequently leak a timer resource. This will cause broken follow up tests at best, and flaky follow up tests at worst. I think this is a real footgun.

I think this is different from the indeterminate state of follow ups after errors that already exists right now, because in that case code execution of the earlier test is terminated in most cases (because the exception bubbled up).

With timeouts, code is still executing after the timeout fires. This may be very strange to people.

I don't have a good solution to this, and maybe this tradeoff is fine, but I want to throw some ideas out here:

- Should timeouts affect each test, or the entire module as a whole? For the latter, we can terminate execution of that test module after timeout, preventing this issue.
- If we stick with per test timeouts, should we fail fast (run no follow up tests) the module after the timeout occurs? We can then also terminate the entire test module after timeout. This would also prevent the issue.

Hey @lucacasonato, thanks a lot for your input 😊 

The example of the leaking `setTimeout` was an excellent catch and indeed a serious situation to consider. Thank you for noticing that.

Given what you've said, I think we have two questions to answer:

1. Whether the current behaviour is consistent or we need to change it
2. Whether we'll need more features to improve handling the situation you described

# 1. Analyzing the current behaviour

Regarding analyzing whether the current behaviour is consistent, my view is that the situation you describe is a resource and operations leak. Therefore, first and foremost, **we should ensure that sanitizing both asynchronous and synchronous tests leads to consistent results**.

Take the following test file, for example:

``` 
Deno.test("first", () => {
  console.log(Deno.resources());
  setTimeout(() => {}, 2000);
  console.log(Deno.resources());
});

Deno.test("second", () => {
  console.log(Deno.resources());
});
```

In this test file, you'll see that the first test creates a resource that hangs. Therefore, it causes the `first` test to fail. On the other hand, the `second` test still runs just fine, even though the hanging timeout from the first test could've had unexpected side effects and/or made the second test flaky.

Now, let's see what happens when we have the same situation, but with a test that times out:

```ts
Deno.test("first", { timeout: 1000 }, async () => {
  console.log(Deno.resources());
  const timerPromise = new Promise((resolve) => setTimeout(resolve, 2000));
  console.log(Deno.resources());
  await timerPromise;
});

Deno.test("second", () => {
  console.log(Deno.resources());
});
```

In this situation and the previous one, the `first` test fails, and the second still runs and succeeds despite the possibility for the existing hanging timer to interfere with subsequent tests.

The only difference between these two scenarios is that the error message in the first scenario mentions hanging resources, while the error message in the second scenario mentions a timeout.

> 👉 We don't throw a sanitizer-related error because [**we only sanitize resources if a test succeeds**](https://github.com/denoland/deno/blob/4799aaac15285833341d1e0471a2559bd325982f/runtime/js/40_testing.js#L274). Also, it isn't that useful to throw a sanitizer-related error if the test has already failed.
> 👉 The same happens with operations. We do know that there have been leaking operations, but we do not throw an error mentioning leaking ops because the test has already failed at that time.

**Considering the above, I believe that the current behaviour is consistent with what currently happens when there are hanging timers**. Consequently, I'd prefer not to change this PR's current behaviour.

# 2. Proposed way forward

Even though the current behaviour is consistent with this PR's behaviour, I do agree that we need changes to prevent hanging resources/leaking ops from interfering with subsequent tests.

In my view, the runner should treat each test as an individual unit of execution. Therefore, the failure of a single test shouldn't interfere with others in the same file. I think so because it's very frustrating not to know the results of other tests I may have to debug because a previous test failed. Furthermore, separating tests into multiple files is an arbitrary decision, and I'd be a bit surprised to learn that the runner is using test files as a unit of execution.

Finally, a third reason for thinking of tests as an individual execution unit is that it allows for more flexible scheduling and handling, as it would be necessary for timing out synchronous tests (as described in #13609).

# 3. Final recommendation

Considering the two sections above, my recommendation is that:

1. We do not change the current PRs behaviour to keep its scope small (considering its behaviour is already consistent with the existing runner's)
2. We create a separate issue to ensure hanging timers wouldn't interfere with subsequent tests (which would probably end up being a consequence of #13609 anyway).

❓ One thing we could discuss, however, is whether we'd prefer to throw sanitizer errors rather than timeout errors in this situation. I don't think we should, considering that a timeout indicates an issue that needs to be solved _before_ leaking resources/ops anyway, but I'm open to suggestions, of course.

I don't think I clarified my actual concern well enough. I am aware of the behavior being the same in so far that a previous failing test (either timeout or exception) can leak existing resources into other tests.

My concern is that when a test times out, **the code keeps executing**. This is different when an exception occurs. The code is done executing, because the exception bubbled up.

The problem with the continued execution is that it results in very un-intuitive behavior:

```js
Deno.test("first", { timeout: 1000 }, async () => {
  await new Promise(res => setTimeout(res, 2000);
  const file = await Deno.open("./README.md");
  await new Promise(res => setTimeout(res, 3000);
  file.close();
});

Deno.test("second", async () => {
  await new Promise(res => setTimeout(res, 2000);
});
```

Now the second test doesn't just fail with a leaking timer resource (which is already confusing), but it fails with a leaking file resource, which makes even less sense to the user, because that file should have never been opened as the timeout occurred.

### I.e. it is not intuitive that code in the test function continues executing after the timeout marks the test as "failed".

This is especially important for synchronous timeouts. In synchronous environments, the code _has_ to be terminated. You can not leave the sync code running and just mark the test as skipped, because if there is some sync code blocking execution then no other tests can be run, because they are blocked on the sync code. It would be confusing if async and sync environments behaved differently in this regard of termination.

---

As for the unit of execution being the test: it currently isn't, and it would probably be a backwards incompatible change to change this. The current unit of execution is a module. This also has some desirable effects: namely that global scope only executes once per module, rather than once per test. The latter can be very confusing.

@lucasfcosta Sorry I never responded to your last message. To answer your question:

