@aapoalas this is an interesting thought and similar to one i was having myself if i understand you correctly. i don't know enough about internals of Resources in Deno as yet but the pattern i have found most performant for this kind of thing is along these lines:

- allocate an arraybuffer in JS
- pass this arraybuffer into C++/Rust where pointer to and size of data is stored in a Map with an integer key that is returned to JS
- when performing any ops on this buffer, just pass in the integer key and have C++/Rust lookup the struct. The struct looks something like this and can be mapped onto another ArrayBuffer which JS side can read values from using TypedArray/DataView
```
struct rawBuffer {
  uint32_t len;
  int32_t read;
  int32_t written;
  uint32_t id;
  uint8_t* data;
};

std::map<int, rawBuffer*> buffers;
```
We could also store a persistent v8 handle on this struct to ensure the buffer is not moved or collected and expect consumer to explicitly release it when they are done (which is likely never as these will be buffers used repeatedly).

then, the op code becomes something like this, which is very performant as only passing an integer key from JS to C++/Rust, writing the results into internal struct and not returning any value.

```
void just::html::EscapeSIMDRaw2(const FunctionCallbackInfo<Value> &args) {
  just::html::rawBuffer* src = just::html::buffers[Local<Integer>::Cast(args[1])->Value()];
  src->written = args[0].As<String>()->WriteUtf8(args.GetIsolate(), (char*)src->data, src->len, &src->read, 
    v8::String::HINT_MANY_WRITES_EXPECTED | 
    v8::String::REPLACE_INVALID_UTF8 | 
    v8::String::NO_NULL_TERMINATION
  );
  just::html::rawBuffer* dest = just::html::buffers[Local<Integer>::Cast(args[2])->Value()];
  dest->written = hesc_escape_html(dest->data, src->data, src->written);
  args.GetReturnValue().Set(String::NewFromUtf8(args.GetIsolate(), (char*)dest->data, 
    NewStringType::kNormal, dest->written).ToLocalChecked());
}
```

of course, there is no error checking in this example, but it seems we can avoid that overhead now with fast calls and once the code is optimized by JIT we should be on fast path where we can bypass the expensive error checks.

