Alright, so the reason for this error is that during analysis of a module, deno internally (in `proc_state.rs`) makes note of all NPM dependencies and loads them ahead of time. Now, at least for the main module (entry point module) the handling is all-or-nothing: All statically analysed NPM dependencies are loaded before the main module is actually executed, and all of them must succeed or the main module is considered invalid.

The fix would be something akin to handling static imports and dynamic imports differently in `prepare_module_load` in `proc_state.rs` but that's a bit beyond this PR I think. Luckily I have a workaround: If the NPM dependencies are not statically analysable then they won't be included in the all-or-nothing handling above. So @bershanskiy if you just change in your tests the `import("npm:doesn't-exist")` calls to `import('npm:${namePart}')` using template literals, then Deno won't understand that you're importing an NPM module during initial parsing time. The download attempt of the module will move to runtime and an error will be properly thrown as you'd expect.

@dsherret I think this handling of statically analysable NPM dependencies is something to take into account in your refactor moving NPM specifiers' handling to deno_graph.

