@wille-io I spoke with @lucacasonato and here's what he suggested:
1. Go with `resolveCertificate` API instead:
```ts
interface ServeTlsOptions extends ServeOptions {
  /** The default server certificate in PEM format. */
  cert?: string;
  /** The default server private key in PEM format. */
  key?: string;

  /** A function to return a certificate for a connection, based on the name
   * specified in the TLS ClientHello packet (SNI). If the function throws or
   * returns a rejected promise, the connection with the client will be aborted.
   *
   * The results of this function are cached by name, if the returned
   * certificate and key are valid. This function will never be invoked in
   * parallel for the same name.
   *
   * Multiple names may return the same certificate and key. */
  resolveCertificate?(name: string): Promise<{ cert: string; key: string }>;
}
```
It's a bit more cumbersome to handle but provides a lot more flexibility due to not requiring list of hostnames upfront. This would allow a library to implement something like https://caddyserver.com/docs/automatic-https, which would be really dope.
2. `op_accept_tls` can return either a ready TLS socket as a rid, <b>or a want-to-be-tls socket that is missing a certificate. in the latter case it returns a hostname and a rid. in that latter case it creates a ‘want-to-be-tls socket’ resource.</b>
3. in case a ready TLS socket is returned, yield it to the usercode, <b>if a want-to-be-tls socket is returned, invoke the callback with the hostname and await a response. if the callback fails, close the ‘want-to-be-tls socket’ resource. if it succeeds, call `op_accept_tls_finish(rid, cert, key)` to upgrade the  ‘want-to-be-tls socket’ resource into a ‘tls socket’ resource</b>

Parts in <b>bold</b> are what is needed to implement that. Let me know how that sounds and if you're interested in tackling this.

